<p>One of the alternatives to Python's <a href="https://mail.python.org/pipermail/python-dev/2005-September/056846.html" rel="nofollow noreferrer">conditional expression</a></p>

<pre><code>"yes" if boolean else "no"
</code></pre>

<p>is the following:</p>

<pre><code>{True:"yes", False:"no"}[boolean]
</code></pre>

<p>which has the following nice extension:</p>

<pre><code>{True:"yes", False:"no", None:"maybe"}[boolean_or_none]
</code></pre>

<p>The shortest alternative remains:</p>

<pre><code>("no", "yes")[boolean]
</code></pre>

<p>but there is no alternative to</p>

<pre><code>yes() if boolean else no()
</code></pre>

<p>if you want to avoid the evaluation of <code>yes()</code> <em>and</em> <code>no()</code>, because in</p>

<pre><code>(no(), yes())[boolean]  # bad
</code></pre>

<p>both <code>no()</code> and <code>yes()</code> are evaluated.</p>
